summaries.title: Building Inclusive Engineering Teams
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: First-Generation Challenges in Navigating University Systems
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Developing Leadership Confidence Through Robotics Projects
summaries.summaryText: Ethan described how leading design sprints in the robotics club refined his communication and teamwork skills. He recognized his relative advantage from prior exposure to engineering through his family, and expressed an interest in mentoring peers with less background experience. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Family Support and Pressure as a Dual Motivation
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniel’s parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Community and Peer Mentorship as Anchors
summaries.summaryText: Peer mentors and cultural centers helped Luis navigate isolation as a first-gen Latino student. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 1/4]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Intersection of Culture and Academic Identity
themes.description: Cultural expectations of excellence create dual pressure for first-gen students in technical majors. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 1]

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Ethan on the value of diverse collaboration.

quotes.quoteText: If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Ethan describing inclusive team leadership philosophy.

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of — that’s when privilege clicked for me. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Ethan reflecting on his exposure to early STEM opportunities.

quotes.quoteText: My parents say, ‘Just do your best,’ but I can tell they really mean, ‘Don’t waste this chance we gave you.’ [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on implicit cultural pressure from family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include ‘learning journeys’ in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Enhance First-Gen Orientation Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Create summer bridge programs for high school students
Offer needs-based scholarships for pre-college engineering camps

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
